cs.SI, cs.SD, cs.LG, cs.DS, cs.NE

The paper deals with the problem of predicting the category of arbitrary networks based on their structural properties. This falls under the domain of network science and machine learning, which are covered by several sub-categories in arXiv CS. The most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as the paper deals with predicting categories of networks such as re-tweets and brain activity. The second likely sub-category is cs.SD (Sound and Music Computing) as the paper mentions the use of synthetic graphs from five different network models. The third likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning) as the paper uses a random forest classifier to predict the categories of networks. The fourth likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as the paper deals with the structural properties of networks. The fifth likely sub-category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as the paper mentions the use of machine learning techniques to predict the categories of networks.
